Investigating Ad Exposure Across Product Categories

Introduction to Ad Tracking Data.

This visual story dives into the world of internet ads, exploring how often they pop up in our daily lives and what we think of them. I collected this data myself, logging the ads I encountered over a period of 21 days, capturing 21 responses to get a sense of my own ad experience. It covers six product categories: Clothing & Accessories, Electronics & Gadgets, Food & Drinks, Health & Fitness, Financial Services, and Entertainment (Movies, Games, Events). I tracked how many times I saw ads for these topics each day, noting the platforms they appeared on Instagram, YouTube, Google, Streaming services, or Other. I also recorded the type of ad I saw, whether it was a Text ad, Image ad, Video ad, Pop-up ad, or Sponsored content, and rated their relevance to my interests on a scale from Very relevant to Very irrelevant. For the average person, ads are a constant part of the day either scrolling Instagram during a break, watching a YouTube video after university or work, or browsing Google for a recipe, only to be met with a flashy video ad or a sneaky pop-up. My data reflects that personal journey, showing how these ads has gotten its way into my life, from morning scrolls to late night movie binges.

Ad Frequency for Clothing Ads

This histogram dives into how often I ran into Clothing ads while tracking my own ad experiences. The bars show how many times I saw these ads, with the x axis ranging from 0 to about 25 times seen, and the y axis counting up to 3 instances per bin. What stands out is the two big peaks—one around 15 times and another at 20 times—each hitting a count of 3. There’s a bit of a dip between those peaks, and the counts taper off on either side, with fewer ads seen below 10 or above 20 times. This tells me Clothing ads weren’t just a one time thing in my day—they were a steady presence, especially in that 15–20 range.

For the average person they see . Imagine scrolling through Instagram during a lunch break and seeing a Clothing ad for a new jacket, then later on YouTube, there’s another one for sneakers while you’re watching a tutorial. That’s the kind of thing I was logging—my own moments of seeing these ads across platforms like Instagram, YouTube, and Google. I noticed these Clothing ads a lot, maybe because I’d been browsing for new outfits, or maybe brands are just pushing hard to catch people like me who love a good deal. Either way, this graph shows how those ads became a regular part of my online routine, popping up just enough to grab my attention without totally overwhelming me.

Exploring Daily Ad Patterns

This scatter plot is a peek into how many ads I saw each day while tracking my ad experiences. The x axis lists 20 response points, and the y-axis shows ad frequencies from 5 to 25. Each dot showing the day of the week is colored by a palette of teal, salmon, blue, pink, green, yellow, and beige. What jumps out is how Mondays and Wednesdays have some of the highest dots, reaching up to 25 ads—those days were buzzing with ad activity! Sundays, on the other hand, are mostly below 10, showing a quieter vibe. The dots are spread out across the week, but there’s a clear pattern of more ads midweek, with some days like Tuesday and Friday floating around the 15 mark.

For the average person, this kind of ad pattern fits right into their routine. Think about a typical Monday—you’re back to work, scrolling YouTube during lunch, and boom, a Video ad for Electronics pops up. By Wednesday, you’re on Instagram, and there’s a Sponsored post for Food & Drinks. That’s what I was capturing in my data—my own ad encounters on platforms like Instagram and Streaming services. Seeing more ads on Mondays and Wednesdays makes sense; maybe brands know I’m more active online then, catching me during my busiest browsing moments. This graph really shows how the ad world seems to pick up its pace midweek in my online life, slowing down a bit on weekends when I’m maybe just chilling with a movie.

Ad Relevance

This pie chart takes a closer look at how relevant I thought these ads were to my interests while tracking my own ad experiences. The chart is split into five slices, each with a distinct color: orange for “Somewhat relevant,” teal for “Very relevant,” blue for “Neutral,” pink for “Somewhat irrelevant,” and green for “Very irrelevant.” The biggest slice by far is the orange “Somewhat relevant” one, taking up almost half the pie—probably around 40% of my 50 responses. Next up is the teal “Very relevant” slice, which is smaller, maybe about 20%, followed by the blue “Neutral” slice at around 15%. The pink “Somewhat irrelevant” and green “Very irrelevant” slices are the smallest, each under 10%, showing I rarely felt the ads were totally off the mark. It’s like most of the time I was thinking, “Yeah, this ad’s kind of okay for me,” with only a few really hitting the spot or completely missing it.

For the average person, rating ad relevance is part of the daily online dance. Imagine you’re streaming a show and a Video ad for Entertainment pops up—you might think, “Hey, that’s pretty relevant!” Then you’re on Google, and a Pop-up ad for Financial Services shows up while you’re looking for a recipe—not so much. That’s the kind of thing I was doing with my data, logging my reactions to ads across platforms like Instagram and YouTube. The big “Somewhat relevant” slice makes sense for me—maybe I saw a lot of Clothing ads that were close to my style but not perfect, or Electronics ads that were interesting but not urgent. This graph shows how most ads I saw were in that middle ground, connecting just enough to keep me curious but leaving room for brands to step up their game.

Conclusion

This journey through my personal internet ad data has been eye opening! I’ve seen how Clothing ads kept a steady presence in my feeds, how Mondays and Wednesdays brought a flood of ads mostly on Instagram and YouTube—and how most ads I saw were somewhat relevant but not life changing. These simple plots and a bit of data crunching have shown me how ads weave into my online life, from morning scrolls to late night streaming on services like Netflix. Sure, this is just a snapshot from my own 50 responses and might have some quirks like maybe I noticed more ads when I was bored—but it’s a cool reminder of how data can help me spot trends and maybe even understand why I’m seeing that same Clothing ad for the 20th time!
